<TEXT>
vice president dan quayle doesnt abide 
discrimination at golf clubs his office says but he still plays 
at one of the most exclusive allmale courses near the capital as 
an honorary member 
quayle on friday canceled a second round of golf at the 
allwhite cypress point golf club near monterey calif after he 
learned the facility was mired in a racial controversy said his 
press secretary david beckwith 
he had played there thursday unaware beckwith said that the 
club was ruled ineligible for its share of the 1991 atampt pebble 
beach national proam tournament next month because it has no black 
members 
quayle was unwilling to leave any impression that he condones 
any form of discrimination so he left california and returned to 
vail colo where he had been on a skiing vacation beckwith said 
but the spokesman said he could not explain why quayle is an 
honorary member of the burning tree club in suburban bethesda md 
which bars women from its course 
he encourages all clubs to adopt nondiscriminatory 
policies beckwith said 
he said quayle is not a duespaying member the clubs 
membership roster lists him as an honorary member 
burning trees members include some of the nations most 
powerful political leaders the 68yearold club last year lost a 
court battle to regain a tax break the maryland legislature had 
revoked in 1986 because of its refusal to admit women as members or 
generally allow them on the property 
quayles chief of staff bill kristol said in a telephone 
interview i dont think playing at burning tree is inconsistent 
with opposing discrimination lots of people with good 
antidiscriminatory records have played golf at burning tree 
cypress point does admit women but it refused to admit black 
members in time to conform to the professional golfers 
associations new guidelines that hold no host tournament club can 
discriminate against blacks or women 
we have no discrimination clauses in our bylaws but we do not 
have black members said club pro jim langley we have a 
waiting list of approved applicants of several years and we 
couldnt bypass them 
quayle went to cypress point at the invitation of his college 
roommate mark rolfing a media golf commentator according to 
local sources he teed off thursday with two cypress point club 
