<TEXT>
indonesia plans to try leaders of a 
littleknown insurgent movement next month and overseas human 
rights groups should monitor the trial one of the groups says 
about 40 defendants face charges in three cities for alleged 
activity in behalf of aceh merdeka or free aceh an armed 
liberation group operating at the northern tip of sumatra sidney 
jones executive director of asia watch said friday 
the cases could provide accounts of torture killings and other 
atrocities that have become routine in counterinsurgency campaigns 
in the aceh region and elsewhere in indonesia asia watch said 
in aceh there is no question that both sides have engaged in 
atrocities but the scale and brutality of the indonesian response 
is out of all proportion to the threat posed by the insurgents 
ms jones said 
the current outbreak of violence in the aceh region began 18 
months ago and the combined death toll on both sides has been 
estimated as high as 1000 asia watch said in a yearend report on 
the situation 
corpses continue to be found along roads and rivers in three 
districts of aceh it said the indonesian military appears to 
have systematically killed at least dozens and perhaps hundreds of 
suspected aceh merdeka supporters in revenge as a deterrent and as 
a means of disposing of prisoners 
human rights violations in the aceh region fall into a pattern 
of systematic and gross abuses already well established in 
indonesia the report said 
it cited similar abuses in past disturbances in east timor east 
irian and central java torture techniques reported from aceh 
occur throughout indonesia including in jakarta police stations 
torture reported from aceh and standard throughout indonesia is 
the placing of a chair or table over the suspects foot which the 
interrogator then sits on it said 
indonesia does not admit international human rights 
organizations for official observation but asia watch hopes to be 
represented unofficially at the open trials in the cities of medan 
banda aceh and lhokseumawe ms jones said by telephone from new 
york 
asia watch is affiliated with helsinki watch and other groups 
that promote observance of human rights set forth in the 1975 
helsinki eastwest agreement 
ms jones said she discussed human rights at a meeting with 
indonesian foreign minister ali alatas at the united nations this 
fall and later visited sumatra privately 
she quoted alatas as telling her that asia watch could come to 
his country officially when it stops taunting indonesia she 
said she replied that international pressure is critical to bring 
about improvements in the human rights situation and what they 
call taunting we call constructive criticism 
