<TEXT>
health and human services secretary louis 
sullivan says millions of sick elderly or poor americans will 
suffer if proposed cuts in his budget are implemented 
the reductions would leave sullivans agency unable to maintain 
current services in programs like medicare and social security the 
secretary said in a letter to the white house protesting the office 
of management and budgets proposed cuts he said the result would 
be longer processing times for claims 
sullivans letter said also that the omb proposal would provide 
inadequate funds to turn more attention to prenatal care and 
expansion of programs to combat lead poisoning breast cancer 
tuberculosis and aids as the department wants to do 
the letter a copy of which was obtained by the associated press 
on friday was sent last friday night to omb director richard 
darman first word of it appeared in fridays new york times 
a department budget official said that during the past week much 
progress had been made in negotiations with omb but he declined to 
give specifics the negotiations are continuing he said 
the letter said that cuts in funds for administration of the 
health care financing administration which handles medicare and 
medicaid and the social security administration could hurt our 
ability to respond to the needs of 50 million aged and disabled 
beneficiaries 
kevin moley hhs assistant secretary for management and budget 
said that while the figure of 50 million was correct when the 
letter was written a week ago it is far fewer today than last 
week and we expect to resolve those issues by the time we announce 
our budget 
moley declined to say how much money was in dispute and the 
letter did not spell out the total 
sullivans letter of appeal is part of the annual budgetmaking 
process after a department drafts a budget request omb reviews 
it makes changes and sends the resulting proposal called a pass 
back to the department the department then negotiates with omb 
and if still not satisfied may appeal to the president himself 
it is rare that any agency head is satisfied with ombs pass 
back 
president bush will give his budget proposal covering the 1992 
fiscal year beginning on oct 1 1991 to congress in early 
february 
ombs pass back to hhs would cut medicare by 27 billion in 
addition to the nearly 6 billion agreed to in the 
deficitreduction package approved by the administration and 
congress in october the extra cuts would come from payments to 
physicians and hospitals 
the proposed cuts in administrative expenses of social security 
would increase the backlog of telephone calls and mean more busy 
signals sullivans letter said 
sullivan said the department needs an additional 82 million 
beyond what omb would provide for efforts to get highrisk women 
into prenatal care these efforts would help reduce the united 
states high infant mortality rate and reduce costs for care of 
premature infants he said 
sullivan also wants 143 million beyond ombs proposal for 
programs that increase access to health care for minorities and the 
disadvantaged 
the secretary also told darman he wants to further decrease the 
low income home energy assistance program to 468 million which 
has been running at about 1 billion a year in recent years and 
target it to the northeast states where lowincome residents are 
most likely to use fuel oil to heat their homes 
</TEXT>
