prime minister toshiki kaifus 10monthold cabinet 
resigned today after intense party pressure to allow other senior 
politicians to hold prestigious government posts a top official 
said 
kaifus new cabinet was to be announced this evening many key 
ministers are expected to retain their posts and no major policy 
changes were expected 
the makeup of the new cabinet has been the subject of intense 
debate within the governing liberal democratic party kaifu is 
strongly opposed to demands by some senior party leaders to bring 
back politicians who were tainted by an influencepeddling scandal 
last year 
whether kaifu can keep his cabinet free of politicians linked to 
the scandal in which the recruit jobplacement conglomerate 
offered lucrative unlisted stock to influential politicians is 
being viewed by analysts as a test of his political clout 
there was no immediate official announcement of the cabinet 
reshuffle but politicians leaving an afternoon meeting with kaifu 
indicated the resignations had been tendered 
a top government official speaking on condition of anonymity 
confirmed that all 21 cabinet members had handed letters of 
resignation to kaifu upon his request 
nothing is going to change except faces in the cabinet profile 
book said masaya ito a prominent political analyst who served 
as secretary to the late prime minister hayato ikeda 
japans cabinet is typically reshuffled annually to give 
desirable assignments to senior lawmakers of the liberal democratic 
party 
the party is comprised of five major factions each headed by a 
powerful politician who aspires to become prime minister and to win 
cabinet posts for his allies 
because he belongs to the smallest faction kaifu is regarded as 
having a weak power base and needs to compromise with other faction 
leaders 
kaifu originally had said he would not announce a change before 
the new year in an effort to display some independence but 
apparently changed his mind after meeting friday afternoon with 
ichiro ozawa the partys powerful secretary general 
