<TEXT>
americans paid more attention to the persian 
gulf crisis than to any other news story in 1990 a year in which 
domestic news reports were dominated by international events a 
survey shows 
twothirds of the public closely followed stories about the 
iraqi invasion of kuwait and the deployment of us forces in the 
region over the last five months according to the survey by the 
times mirror center for the people and the press 
but americans showed little interest in the historic fall of 
communism in almost all of eastern europe and the economic and 
political turmoil in the soviet union the survey said that at no 
point did more than 30 percent of americans closely follow these 
events 
the mideast events also figured in the most closely followed 
domestic news story of the year sixtytwo percent of those 
surveyed said they regularly read stories about soaring gasoline 
prices in august and september 
by comparison reports in november about the declining economy 
attracted only 39 percent of the readers on a regular basis 
stories leaing up to and including the november general election 
caught the regular attention of only 38 percent as did stories 
last january about the war against drugs 
only one other news event also involving us soldiers fighting 
abroad caught the close attention of more than a majority 
americans sixty percent of americans regularly read stories about 
the us invasion of panama although us troops invaded panama in 
december 1989 their presence in the country and numerous news 
stories continued into 1990 
according to the survey the times mirror news interest index 
public interest in some issues shifted significantly during the 
year 
last spring only 18 percent of the public paid close attention 
to stories about the first signs of economic problems by september 
that percentage had increased to 29 percent and in november it was 
39 percent 
there was only scant attention to the nations budget deficit 
last spring when rep dan rostenkowski dill proposed a deficit 
reduction plan during the summer as congress debated a budget 
package 18 percent of the readers were following the issue closely 
with public attention increasing to 34 percent by the fall amid 
threats to shut down the federal government 
interest in news concerning president bush also fluctuated 
widely during the year 
when bush attended the drug summit in columbia last february 
only 22 percent of the public paid close attention to news stories 
about the visit criticism of the president on his changing 
position on taxes and his persian gulf policy caught the close 
attention of slightly less than a third of the public 
by contrast three out of four people read last march about 
bushs distaste for broccoli 
sensational crimes and trials brought substantial public 
interest during 1990 
news about the serial killings in gainesville fla attracted 
more public attention 36 percent than any other crime story 
during the year twentyeight percent of the readers followed the 
drug arrest of mayor marion barry of washington dc but interest 
waned only 16 percent paid close attention to stories about 
barrys conviction on some of the charges 
some stories attracted less public interest than expected 
despite the extensive coverage of the nomination of david souter 
to the us supreme court only about 15 percent followed the event 
closely and more than half of the people surveyed said they 
strongly felt too much was written about the marital breakup of 
donald and ivana trump twelve percent of the public said they 
closely followed the affair 
here are a few other major news events and their interest 
quotient 
the supreme court decision affirming the right to burn the 
flag 24 percent 
the super bowl 22 percent 
the controversy surrounding roseanne barrs singing of the 
national anthem 21 percent 
continuing news last june about the savings and loan scandal 
18 percent 
the election in nicaragua 19 percent 
the death of 87 people in a first at a new york city social 
club 28 percent 
political changes in the soviet union and eastern europe 26 to 
28 percent 
among the news stories in the survey that attracted the least 
interest were the united nations childrens summit 6 percent 
civil war in cambodia 4 percent and actor tom cruises separation 
from his wife 2 percent 
the 1990 survey reflects monthly telephone polls of about 1200 
adults nationwide each monthly survey has a margin of error of 
plus or minus 3 percent 
</TEXT>
