<TEXT>
california stopped telling casual marijuana 
users smoke a joint go to jail 15 years ago but the federal 
governments new version smoke a joint lose your drivers 
license promises to rekindle debate over the states pot law 
a littlenoted amendment to a new federal highway funding law 
seeks to use federal funding as a weapon against liberal state drug 
laws it would particularly affect california and new york because 
of those states relatively liberal marijuana laws and large 
amounts of federal funding 
the federal law calls for every state to pass a law in 199192 
requiring a sixmonth driver license suspension for anyone 
convicted of violating any drug law including possession of 
marijuana for personal use 
states that refuse could lose 5 percent of their federal highway 
aid in the 12 months starting oct 1 1993 that would be 60 
million at current levels of aid to california said the 
amendments sponsor rep gerald solomon rny the amendment 
passed in july 
new yorks penalty would be an estimated 16 million said state 
transporation department spokesman david ernst 
the penalty would become 10 percent two years later 
the penalty appears modest in light of californias 55 billion 
budget but with 1991s state deficit projected as high as 10 
billion any potential loss of revenue is a sensitive issue 
govelect pete wilson has not taken a position on driver 
license suspensions but press secretary bill livingstone said 
wilson agrees with outgoing federal drug overseer william bennett 
that californias drug laws are too lenient 
wilson cannot require the democraticcontrolled legislature to 
pass a license suspension law but his position could determine the 
fiscal impact on the state solomons amendment lets a state avoid 
a monetary penalty only if both the legislature and the governor 
oppose the requirement of license suspensions 
california liberalized its marijuana law in 1975 possession of 
an ounce or less which previously could be prosecuted as a felony 
with a state prison sentence is now subject to a 100 fine with 
no jail time or permanent criminal record 
the state requires a fourmonth license suspension for drunken 
drivers but doesnt suspend licenses for drinking drug use or drug 
possession unrelated to driving 
any action by the new york state legislature on the requirement 
probably wouldnt come for several years after the federal 
government issues details of how the highway program would be run 
were aware of the law were waiting for the regulations to 
see how to best proceed said christopher cernik counsel to 
assemblyman michael bragman chairman of the assembly 
transportation committee 
a spokesman for the national organization for the reform of 
marijuana laws gordon brownell called the mandatory license 
suspension tantamount to a recriminalization and a federally 
imposed interference with california public policy 
in california the chairmen of the legislative committees that 
would handle the license suspension bill both criticized the 
federal law but declined to predict the states response 
sen bill lockyer chairman of the senate judiciary committee 
said he generally favored minimal sentences for possessing small 
amounts of marijuana but was noncommittal on the license 
suspension proposal 
assemblyman john burton chairman of the assembly public safety 
committee said he opposed the license suspension as unwarranted 
federal interference as well as on its merits 
driving under the influence of a drug is one thing possessing 
it is another he said 
