<TEXT>
in july 1989 a band of reporters quit a 
prochina newspaper in hong kong because they opposed beijings 
crackdown on a movement for democracy and wanted to report the 
truth 
they started a magazine on china and called it contemporary it 
was going to be different independent and analytical 
but a year after the first issue hit the stands contemporary is 
foundering hurt by falling circulation a virtual boycott on 
advertising and a lack of reporters willing to brave criticism from 
hardline chinese officials to report the news 
whats happening to contemporary sums up whats happening to 
hong kongs once freewheeling press 
1997 the year communist china takes control of the british 
colony looms as a dangerous deadline for the media in hong kong 
reporters and editors say they face a choice either dont 
insult china or leave the profession or even the territory 
contemporary for example has lost about half of its 15 
founding members all of whom came from the hardline wen wei po 
newspaper some have immigrated to the west others have taken jobs 
at less controversial publications 
already one religious newsletter is moving its headquarters from 
hong kong to bangkok several other international publications are 
believed to be exploring the same 
were adopting a waitandsee attitude said barry wain 
publisher of the americanowned asian wall street journal our 
attitude is that weve made no plans to leave 
but the bulk of hong kongs 60 plus daily newspapers and 600 
plus magazines live and breath the territory they have nowhere to 
go 
to succeed reporters at chinese and englishlanguage 
publications say one has to practice selfcensorship and there are 
fewrewards for bucking the trend 
exploring sensitive topics scares advertisers loses reporters 
access to news conferences and doesnt necessarily win more 
readers 
in the last few months contemporarys circulation has dropped 
from 10000 to 8000 despite a series of wellwritten pieces on 
chinas military and several scoops about the workings of the 
xinhua news agency chinas de facto embassy to the territory 
its reporters are now banned from china 
when i started this thing i firmly believed that a society as 
rich as hong kong could support a serious magazine said ching 
cheong contemporarys editorinchief now im dismayed to find 
thats not the case 
cheong said the magazine needed to reach 15000 to break even 
and thats with advertising 
but contemporarys ad space has dwindled to nothing due to 
apparent pressure from beijingcontrolled companies on potential 
advertisers cheong said 
one americaneducated advertising executive speaking on 
condition of anonymity said he received a phone call earlier this 
year from a chineseowned company asking him why his firm placed 
ads in contemporary 
it was subtle but the message was clear if we wanted 
mainland business we couldnt deal with contemporary he said 
attempts by journalists to quantify such pressure have failed 
said emily lau a correspondent for the hong kongbased far eastern 
economic review and the president of the hong kong journalists 
association 
several months ago the associations executive committee 
proposed a seminar on the topic no one attended 
its a pretty dismal situation lau said everybody knows 
its happening but nobody has the guts to confront the issue 
under a historic agreement between china and britain the 
chinese have promised to preserve hong kongs way of life for at 
least 50 years after beijing takes over in 1997 clause 5 of the 
agreement guarantees freedom of speech and the press 
but faith in chinas pledge has been shaken in the past year by 
the crackdown on a prodemocracy movement in beijing chinese 
authorities arrested dozens of mainland reporters and editors and 
closed or reorganized under hardline leadership several newspapers 
if they treat their reporters like that how will they treat 
us after 97 asks juan tze a leading political cartoonist in 
the territory 
few reporters and editors in the territory have much trust in 
britains ability to keep china to its word 
the colonial government itself passed a law in 1988 that allows 
the banning of films that could seriously damage relations with 
other countries most notably china it was most recently invoked 
earlier this year when the first half of a taiwanese film 
mainland china 1989 was cut because it included interviews with 
prominent chinese dissidents 
to increase its influence china is also moving into hong kongs 
media business 
in october the xinhua news agency announced the launching of 
chinas first magazine in the territory a glossy periodical named 
bauhinia after hong kongs territorial flower in 1988 several 
beijingowned companies merged to form sinounited publishing ltd 
the largest publishing house and book seller in hong kong 
