<TEXT>
a 32 million judgment against a shipping company 
has done little to improve pay for foreign sailors whose 
substandard wages are hidden by false bookkeeping attorneys and 
industry chaplains said 
the penalty against delicia shipping co was handed down in 
august by us district judge jack tanner in tacoma tanner found 
the company intentionally underpaid 21 filipino seamen who had 
signed shipping articles promising higher wages under the worldwide 
international transport workers federation collective agreement 
the decision hailed as a victory for seamen has become buried 
in months of legal motions petitions and appeals 
richard dodson a baton rouge la attorney for the seamen 
said none has seen a dollar from the case and more than half have 
been blacklisted in the industry and cant get work 
dodson said the case was pending before the 9th us circuit 
court of appeals in san francisco with several more motions and 
hearings possible 
if finally the seafarers win the case then i think its going 
to have a very serious impact on the practice of double 
bookkeeping because most ship owners are just not going to be able 
to afford that kind of penalty said paul chapman of the new 
yorkbased seamens church institute 
double bookkeeping refers to the practice of keeping two sets of 
financial records one is shown to inport union inspectors to 
indicate that sailors are being paid the negotiated standard 
wages the other shows their actual pay sometimes as little as 
onefifth of the first figure 
us law gives federal courts jurisdiction over wage cases 
involving foreign vessels and crews when their voyages end in us 
waters 
the delicia case involved the pine forest a ship flying the 
flag of the south pacific republic of vanuatu which requires that 
sailors sign shipping articles promising the high union wages the 
sailors did not get that pay but each month were required to sign 
a voucher showing they had received it and sign a separate receipt 
for their actual wages tanner found 
chapman said double bookkeeping remained widespread in the 
shipping industry after the decision he said filipino sailors are 
paid as little as 275 a month 
the practice was defended by joseph stacey an attorney for 
delicia part of inui steamship co of japan 
once the filipino seaman is paid as much as the japanese 
seamen they will just use japanese sailors he said 
low wags reflect the realities of the market stacey said 
most filipino seamen are eager to work for the lower wage and 
some resisted the lawsuit brought by their coworkers he asserted 
seamens chaplains said the sailors are afraid to complain even 
through they often are underfed and denied medical attention and 
pay 
they really have to be desperate before they speak they all 
know they would be out of work said the rev norris stoa of the 
seattle seamens center 
the rev john moes of the seamans center christian in seattle 
said he was glad the pine forest case focused attention on double 
bookkeeping 
he asserted that on many other ships sailors work under 
similar conditions but they live in such fear to do anything 
no one at several seamens centers in seattle and tacoma could 
produce a filipino seaman willing to talk about shipboard 
conditions 
of the 21 pine forest defendants 13 have been blacklisted in 
the philippines and cannot get shipping jobs dodson said 
the other eight defendants did not appear in court and continued 
to work on the ship while their filipino union represented them he 
said 
dodson who specializes in maritime law and has worked with the 
seamens church institute said he will represent sailors from the 
fir grove cargo ship against inui next july in a case identical to 
the pine forests 
as long as shipping competition remains intense companies will 
look for methods such as double bookkeeping to hold down costs he 
said 
the vessels cost the same finances fuel and food are the 
same the only place you can possibly save money is in wages to the 
crew so if you want to gain some advantage you engage in some 
nefarious activity such as double bookkeeping dodson said 
</TEXT>
