bombings bank robberies and kidnappings for ransom 
firmenich boldly announced the existence of the montoneros in 
june 1970 by kidnapping and executing former military president 
pedro aramburu 
growing unrest led videla and viola to stage the march 1976 coup 
that overthrew president isabel peron videla became president 
until 1981 when viola took over for a year 
the military stepped down in december 1983 after its disastrous 
defeat in the falklands war with britain 
officials have documented the disappearance of at least 8960 
people in the years after the 1976 coup all are presumed to have 
been kidnapped and executed by the military 
according to testimony in the trials the military burned the 
bodies of some its victims buried others in unmarked graves and 
tossed some from helicopters into the sea thousands of argentine 
families spent years trying to find out what happened to loved 
ones some still dont know 
adolfo perez esquivel winner of the 1980 nobel peace prize 
said the pardons signify the consecration of impunity for the 
authors of grave crimes against humanity 
menem a former governor jailed for nearly five years by videla 
said he was ready to surrender the past and so should his 
countrymen in the interest of national reconciliation and political 
stability 
the pending trials of dirty war officers sparked three army 
insurrections in recent years and the imprisonment of videla and 
the others was the justification for a fourth uprising on dec 3 
the government news agency telam said videla viola massera and 
retired gen pablo riccheri were released from magdalena military 
prison 62 miles south of buenos aires and taken away in a 
helicopter 
firmenich was met outside devoto prison in buenos aires by his 
lawyer and family and whisked away by car 
suarez mason and dismissed general ramon camps were released 
from a military hospital in the capital telam reported 
the others who received pardons including former economy 
minister jose martinez de hoz already had been freed two of the 
former officials norma kennedy and duilio brunello served prison 
terms for fraud charges unrelated to the dirty war 
the pardon cleared a total of 12 men and women of pending 
charges officials said but since the decree has not been 
published it wasnt known if it permits those pardoned to hold 
public office again 
</TEXT>
