soviet union 
western experts say cuba has received about 5 billion yearly in 
economic help and 15 billion in military aid for many of the past 
30 years 
the prensa latina agency in a dispatch from moscow did not 
reveal detailed information about the aid agreement which it said 
was signed after 10 days of talks 
the agreement was reached by the cuban foreign commerce 
minister ricardo cabrisas and the soviet economic relations 
minister konstantin katushev the agency reported 
cuban sources considered the volumes of soviet exports 
adjusted to the requirements of the country in the special period 
facing cuba said the agency monitored in mexico city 
the special period refers to austerity measures adopted to 
confront cubas loss of its friends in eastern europe the 
declining soviet economy and increases in the price of oil which 
cuba must import 
more and more goods are rationed in cuba communist officials 
are being shipped off to do farm work in the countryside and the 
leadership is promoting the use of bicycles to save gasoline 
the agency said cuba agreed to ship sugar nickel citrus 
tobacco alcoholic drinks medications and biotechnology products 
to the soviet union 
in return cuba will receive fuel cereals chemical and metal 
products machinery and other goods as well as continued technical 
and economic assistance 
foreign aid is to be considered by the soviet parliament next 
month and soviet officials have suggested cubas aid may be cut 
the soviet union wants its allies to pay in convertible currency 
at world prices starting jan 1 that would be a major blow to 
cuba which has long enjoyed subsidized soviet exports in return 
for exports shipped at inflated prices 
